      "difficulty_level": "advanced",
      "question": "How does the Parabolic SAR's design enforce trading discipline?",
      "answer": "The Parabolic SAR's design enforces trading discipline through a unique and powerful mathematical rule: the SAR value is not allowed to decrease during an uptrend, and it is not allowed to increase during a downtrend. This is the mathematical enforcement of a one-way trailing stop-loss.\n\nThis implicit rule is a core feature of the indicator's genius. It acts as a 'guard against the propensity to lower a stop-loss,' as its creator, J. Welles Wilder Jr., intended. When a trader is in a profitable long position, and the price begins to correct, the emotional temptation is to 'give the trade more room' by moving the stop-loss further down to avoid being taken out of the position. This is a classic, discipline-breaking mistake that often leads to larger losses.\n\nThe Parabolic SAR makes this impossible. By only ever moving in the direction of the trade, it forces the trader to adhere to a strict, pre-defined risk management plan. The stop-loss can only get tighter, never looser. This builds a core principle of professional trading\u2014letting profits run while cutting losses systematically\u2014directly into the indicator's formula.\n\nIn this way, the Parabolic SAR transcends being a simple analytical tool and becomes a behavioral tool. It acts as a mechanical coach, enforcing the discipline required to manage a trade correctly, removing the emotional component that so often leads to poor decision-making.",
