      "answer": "The calculation for the Parabolic SAR is iterative and depends on whether the indicator is rising (in an uptrend) or falling (in a downtrend).\n\n**Core Formulas**\n\n- **Rising SAR (Uptrend):**\n  `Current SAR = Prior SAR + Prior AF * (Prior EP \u2013 Prior SAR)`\n- **Falling SAR (Downtrend):**\n  `Current SAR = Prior SAR \u2013 Prior AF * (Prior SAR \u2013 Prior EP)`\n\n**Key Components**\n\n- **EP (Extreme Point):** This is the highest high price (for an uptrend) or the lowest low price (for a downtrend) recorded since the current trend began.\n- **AF (Acceleration Factor):** This is a multiplier that dictates the sensitivity and rate of acceleration of the SAR parabola. The AF starts at an initial value and increases by a set 'step' each time a new EP (a new high or new low) is registered in the trend.",
