      "question": "What is the primary limitation of the Parabolic SAR, and what market condition causes the 'whipsaw' effect?",
      "answer": "The Parabolic SAR's greatest strength is also the source of its primary weakness. Its effectiveness is confined exclusively to trending markets. The indicator's performance is notoriously unreliable in flat, ranging, sideways, or choppy market conditions. In these non-trending environments, the indicator will 'whipsaw' back and forth. A whipsaw is a rapid series of false signals, where the indicator flips to 'buy' just as the price moves down, and then flips to 'sell' just as the price moves up. This results in a sequence of small, compounding losses.\n\nThis 'whipsaw' flaw is not a bug; it is an unavoidable, mathematical consequence of the indicator's core design. The SAR is built on the assumption that the price is always in a trend (either up or down). It has no 'neutral' or 'sideways' mode. Because the Acceleration Factor (AF) mechanically moves the SAR dot closer to the price over time\u2014even if the price is perfectly flat\u2014the dot is guaranteed to eventually cross the price. When it does, it will generate a 'reversal' signal, even though no new trend is beginning. This is the root cause of the indicator's failure in ranging markets.",
