      "question": "Why is the naive 'Stop and Reverse' system dangerous, and how can a long-term moving average be used to filter its signals?",
      "answer": "The naive application of the 'Stop and Reverse' (SAR) system\u2014where a trader takes every signal and is always in the market\u2014is highly dangerous. The indicator is mechanical and will always generate signals, regardless of market conditions. In choppy markets, this leads to a series of consecutive losses.\n\nA professional application of the indicator requires a filter to discern which signals to act upon. The most common filter is a long-term moving average (e.g., a 100-period or 200-period MA) to determine the primary or dominant trend.\n\nWith this filter, the strategy is transformed from 'Stop and Reverse' to a more robust 'Exit and Re-enter' system:\n- **If Price > 200-MA (Primary Uptrend):** The trader is only in 'buy mode.' They will use the SAR 'Buy' signal (flip below price) to enter a long trade. They then use the SAR dots to trail their stop-loss. When the SAR 'Sell' signal (flip above price) occurs, they exit the trade, but they do not enter the corresponding short trade. They remain on the sidelines, waiting for the next 'Buy' signal to re-enter in alignment with the primary trend.\n- **If Price < 200-MA (Primary Downtrend):** The trader is only in 'sell mode,' taking only the 'Sell' signals (flips above price) and ignoring all 'Buy' signals as mere exits.",
